  "prompt": "What are some cultural faux pas when interacting with designers?",
  "response": "Here are some potential cultural missteps when interacting with designers:\n\n1. Design-related mistakes\n- Undervaluing their creative process\n- Expecting free spec work\n- Micromanaging design details\n- Not respecting creative boundaries\n- Assuming design is just \"making things look pretty\"\n\n2. Communication errors\n- Using vague or unclear design feedback\n- Comparing design work to templates or competitor designs\n- Dismissing their professional expertise\n- Demanding unrealistic timelines\n- Not providing sufficient context about project goals\n\n3. Professional boundaries\n- Asking for major revisions without additional compensation\n- Expecting immediate turnaround times\n- Treating design as a commodity rather than a specialized skill\n- Failing to provide clear project requirements\n- Changing project scope without discussing compensation\n\n4. Respect-related issues\n- Critiquing design without constructive input\n- Viewing design as a junior/less important role\n- Not acknowledging intellectual property\n- Rushing the creative process\n- Underestimating time required for quality work\n\n5. Payment/professional respect\n- Late payments\n- Negotiating rates inappropriately\n- Not valuing their professional time\n- Expecting free consultations\n- Making last-minute requests\n\nUnderstanding these potential pitfalls can help foster better designer-client relationships.",
